Re-review : Cute, charming yet somewhat forgettable. Cat Quest strips down 
your typical RPG to it's roots, offering very little depth but what is 
there, simplicity, works surprisingly well. By doing the bare minimum, it's 
hard to say whether it'll keep RPG veterans engaged at all but is a great 
addition to the library of newcomers to the genre or much younger gamers in 
general. Combat is simple & the controls are fine. Visuals are lovingly 
crafted and the cat-puns are a love it or hate it type deal. Despite giving 
this four stars, it still remains a forgettable game & the lack of depth is 
my largest gripe. I enjoyed the ride, but I won't be hopping on again any 
time soon.

As for the downsides, the controls can be frustrating, especially when you try to move and cast spells at the same time, since you move by tapping and cast spells by tapping and holding your character.  Purchasing gear from the blacksmith is RNG-based. You purchase chests with in-game currency (there are no IAPs AFAIK), and what you get from them is random.  Besides those two factors, this game is absolutely fantastic, and a good buy in my book.

Many items in the game are functionally useless.  Example: mage robe has almost the same bonus magic as the squire armor, but squire armor also provides Armor.  There are many examples like this.  There are only a handful of "useable" items in the game, everything else is trash.  And the random loot mechanic makes this feel anti-fun

Honest review. While Cat Quest is a fun game, it has a few things that if done differently I would have probably given it 5 stars. One of my main complaints is that the game is just 90 percent random side quests that have really no meaning towards the story. You just pick them up at quest boards and do the same basic tasks over and over. However, the dialogue on the side quests is fun and well written. You spend most of your time leveling up to do the next main quest that lasts 2 minutes. Once you get the key to the golden chests all of the gear you get from quests become useless so you just run around opening golden chests to become stronger so then you feel like you are grinding side quests for experience and that becomes old quick.  My biggest complaint is about the legendaries. Once you receive any one of these items,(which you can do very early on, any challenge the game offered is basically over and the game becomes stale almost instantly. I pretty much lost interest after finding faith and feeling like there was no point anymore. All in all this is a fun game with smooth controls for click and walk and definitely worth the 5 dollars. Just felt the need to put in my 2 cents for what it's worth.------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  Changed my rating to 3 stars because just when I thought the main story was going to open up and become decent it ends abruptly! The main story is like 20 minutes long seriously. Terrible cliffhanger ending.

Beneath this game's silly premise and stupid puns lies a suprisingly engaging action rpg. Mechanics have been stripped down to the basics- a weapon, two armor slots, a handful of spells, and four stats that rise by set amounts every level. Not complex, but that- plus short quests and dungeons- facilitates easy drop-in, drop-out game sessions. The plot never rises above the usual tropes, but what it lacks in originality, it makes up in execution. In fact, it's better structured then most "serious"  RPGs. The characters are likeable, pacing is good, and nothing is wasted- every sidequest chain eventually folds back into the main plot, revealing more of the game lore. The one serious issue is the interface. You tap on an enemy to attack with your sword, yourself to cast a spell, and anywhere else to move there. But combat can get intense, and in the heat of it it's easy to tap the wrong thing. I never got used to it, and died more times due to mis-taps then I'd care to admit. But the game is well-designed enough to be worth pushing through those troubles.

The writing is great, the quests are really creative, indeed the gameplay is repetitive and the ending might could've been delivered better but it is paid off with variety of skills and rich storylines (yes, in plural, in total 60ish interesting sidequests to be done)   Totally recommended this game, I am glad that this is pay-to-play game knowing a game with this quality would be ruined by annoying ads and freemium scheme.
